@NODE Intro "WAEchoD 0.9▀ --> An Introduction."
----------[ @{b}ĪNTRODUCTION@{ub} ]--------------------------------------------------

                                @{u}WAEchoD!@{uu}

WAEchoD (Wild Amiga Echo Daemon) is a Telnet Pager system.  WAEchoD allows
you to be contacted, via the telnet echo port, meaning that people are able
to leave you a three line message indicating there whereabouts, or the IRC
server they are on, etc.

WAEchoD has now been made BBS-Ware.. =D  Consequently, if you use it
more then once, you HAVE to call my BBS :D




@{"  Back to main menu...  " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Require "rEQUIREMENTS oF wAECHOD!"
----------[ @{b}rEQUIREMENTS@{ub} ]--------------------------------------------------

°     An Internet connection
°     A working TCP/IP stack (eg AmiTCP, Miami)
°     Hardly ANY memory :)
°     NO external libraries!
°     s:banner (if you desire a header for your telnet pager)


@{"  Back to main menu...  " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE
@NODE Install "Installing WAEchoD"
----------[ @{b}ĪNSTALLATION@{ub} ]--------------------------------------------------

Installation of WAEchoD comes in three parts... you need to install the main
exe file (WAEchoD) and you need to edit AmiTCP:db/inetd.conf (or whatever is
equivalent to your TCP/IP stack).  You also need to edit/copy s:banner,
which can be a welcome message of 1-6 lines... use the included file as an
example.

1)  Add the following line to AmiTCP:db/inetd.conf


echo        stream tcp dos bin - AmiTCP:serv/WAEchoD


2)  Copy the file WAEchoD to AmiTCP:serv/

3)  Edit/Copy s:banner


   And there you go!  One copy of Wild Amiga Echo Daemon raring to go :)


@{"  Back to main menu...  " link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "uSAGE oF WAEchoD!"
----------[ @{b}uSAGE oF WAEchoD@{ub} ]-------------------------------------------

Test out WAEchoD..!  First of all, run the exe locally (execute it in the
cli by typing the following line)


AmiTCP:serv/WAEchoD


You should see the default welcome banner, and some following instructions.
Simply type your message, and select an option after pressing return after
line 3!

NOTE: Messages can be 1-3 lines only atm :/

The message will be sent through, with a window, displaying the message
automatically opening.

For use via the Internet, simply get people to telnet to your host on
port 7!  For example, for people to telnet to me they have to type:


telnet bradman.demon.co.uk 7


Other examples could be:

telnet joe-bloggs.u-net.com 7
telnet infinity.demon.co.uk 7

And others... you should find that you have a working, useful telnet pager
that people can use to find out if you're online, tell you where they are on
IRC, or just say hello with :)


